<font color="#FF0000">MILITARY INDUSTRIAL COMPLEX</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan 29  6:38:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The issuse of the communists vs. us (the capitalists) <br>
was not created as a myth to rationalize our interventions.<br>
It was a reality. Countries that were moving towards<br>
communism posed a threat to U.S. expansion of markets. We<br>
need to have poorer countries willing to buy our capital <br>
(goods) as a market. Communist countries do not make good<br>
markets. That is the root casue of our opposition to <br>
communism. The defending democracy stuff is the excuse.<br>
If we were so concerned about people's rights we would not have had<br>
the termoil at home (i.e. civil rights movement, black <br>
power, etc). <br><br>
Our involvement in Vietnam and the rest of S.E. Asia was <br>
because we needed to protect our markets and sources of<br>
raw material (oil and rubber etc.) If Vietnam &quot;fell&quot; to<br>
the communists then we feared that so would the rest of <br>
S.E. Asia and beyond. I think this fear was well founded.<br><br>
If we wanted to take control of Vietname we should have <br>
budgeted for sending Coke and Pepsi, McDonalds and<br>
Papa Gino's as well as some TVs and VCRs. This surely <br>
would have helped us to win the Hearts and Minds of the<br>
Vietnamese people where war has failed.<br>
a million copies of &quot;Home Beautiful&quot; or &quot;Life&quot;magazine.
